  <page>
   
    <exercise>
  <title>Limits at Infinity</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Find <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x \to \infty} \frac{3x^2 - 1}{2x^2 - 4x + 3}</m>
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      To find the limit at infinity of a rational function, we divide the numerator and denominator by the highest power of <m>x</m> in the denominator, which is <m>x^2</m>:
      <md>
        <mrow>\lim_{x \to \infty} \frac{3x^2 - 1}{2x^2 - 4x + 3} \amp = \lim_{x \to \infty} \frac{\frac{3x^2}{x^2} - \frac{1}{x^2}}{\frac{2x^2}{x^2} - \frac{4x}{x^2} + \frac{3}{x^2}}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \lim_{x \to \infty} \frac{3 - \frac{1}{x^2}}{2 - \frac{4}{x} + \frac{3}{x^2}}</mrow>
      </md>
      As <m>x \to \infty</m>, the terms <m>\frac{1}{x^2}</m>, <m>\frac{4}{x}</m>, and <m>\frac{3}{x^2}</m> all approach <m>0</m>. Thus:
      <me>\frac{3 - 0}{2 - 0 + 0} = \frac{3}{2}</me>
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
  <title>Derivative by Definition</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      By using the <term>definition</term>, find the derivative of <m>f(x) = \frac{1}{x}</m> for <m>x \neq 0</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      The definition of the derivative is <m>f'(x) = \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{f(x+h) - f(x)}{h}</m>.
      <md>
        <mrow>f'(x) \amp = \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{\frac{1}{x+h} - \frac{1}{x}}{h}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{1}{h} \left( \frac{x - (x+h)}{x(x+h)} \right)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{1}{h} \left( \frac{-h}{x(x+h)} \right)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{-1}{x(x+h)}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = -\frac{1}{x^2}</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
  <title>Continuity of a Piecewise Function</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the function <m>f</m> defined as follows:
      <me>
        f(x) = \begin{cases} 
        x \amp \text{for } x \lt 1 \\
        -x + 1 \amp \text{for } x \ge 1
        \end{cases}
      </me>
      Is <m>f(x)</m> continuous at <m>x=1</m>? Why or why not.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      A function is continuous at <m>x=c</m> if <m>\lim_{x \to c} f(x) = f(c)</m>. We check the one-sided limits at <m>x=1</m>:
      <ol>
        <li><p><m>\displaystyle \lim_{x \to 1^-} f(x) = \lim_{x \to 1^-} (x) = 1</m></p></li>
        <li><p><m>\displaystyle \lim_{x \to 1^+} f(x) = \lim_{x \to 1^+} (-x + 1) = -1 + 1 = 0</m></p></li>
      </ol>
      Since the left-hand limit (<m>1</m>) does not equal the right-hand limit (<m>0</m>), the limit <m>\lim_{x \to 1} f(x)</m> does not exist. Therefore, <m>f(x)</m> is <term>not continuous</term> at <m>x=1</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
  <title>Slope of a Tangent Line</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Find the slope of the tangent line to the curve <m>g(x) = \sqrt{x}</m> at <m>x=4</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      The slope of the tangent line is the derivative <m>g'(4)</m>. 
      First, find the general derivative using the power rule:
      <me>g(x) = x^{1/2} \implies g'(x) = \frac{1}{2}x^{-1/2} = \frac{1}{2\sqrt{x}}</me>
      Now, evaluate at <m>x=4</m>:
      <me>g'(4) = \frac{1}{2\sqrt{4}} = \frac{1}{2(2)} = \frac{1}{4}</me>
      The slope of the tangent line is <m>1/4</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>


  </page>


